A Nigerian-born/British professional in Solar Power, Henry Dumbiri has called on the federal government to focus more on the sustainable element of sourcing energy from non fossil fuel alternatives. Dumbiri, who is the managing director/chief executive officer, Primag Associates Limited, noted that solar power has the potential to become the main electricity generation source in Nigeria. “We are living in unprecedented times where there’s a global call for countries to do more to reduce carbon footprints and diversifying our energy solutions from Oil has the opportunity to turbo charger our economy, create green jobs and enable sustainable, guaranteed power supply.” The managing director, who spoke with newsmen in Abuja yesterday, noted that that Nigeria as a country is very well placed geographically and benefits from an almost 50/50 split between daylight and darkness, adding that power generation shouldn’t really be an issue compared with daylight to darkness ratios experienced by most western countries. While describing the current generation of electricity between 2,500 to 4,000MW as laughable, Dumbiri noted, “Nigeria by harnessing the opportunities with solar energy, Government can channel more resources and political will into building the infrastructures that will allow domestic dwellings, business premises to generate and export excess electricity into the National Grid. He noted that this will reduce the burden on our ageing Power stations around the country.” He maintained that government has a significant role to play by creating an enabling environment for the private sector to deliver affordable generating solutions to Nigerians, while government must design a robust framework to allow competition and provide clarity and consistency with policy pronouncements within the energy sector, which will ultimately drive down cost for the ordinary Nigerian to benefit from solar energy. Dumbiri added that government should also drive the move towards renewable energy as part of our commitment towards international efforts to reduce our dependence on fossil fuels.